name: 4-methyl-2-hexyne
source: American Petroleum Institute. Research Project 44; Selected Values of Properties of Hydrocarbons and Related Compounds. Texas A & M University; College Station; TX; 1973.
Reason: The basic structure for this prediction will be hexane, which typically has a melting point around -95°C. The introduction of a triple bond (alkyne) in 2-hexyne will generally increase the melting point due to increased straightness of the molecule, which allows better packing. This could increase the melting point by approximately +5°C. The methyl group at the 4-position introduces additional branching, which lowers the melting point due to poorer packing. The methyl group effect on melting point could be around -5°C to -10°C. These effects are somewhat counterbalancing. However, the alkyne's effect on increasing the melting point may not be as strong as the effect of the methyl group's branching interruption, leading to a net decrease in the melting point.
